{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594367"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:46:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:46:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15305"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15305"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7996"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63626"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7996"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6965"},{"type":"tags","id":"8760"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20859"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63626"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGallstones are common in Western populations, with a prevalence of between 10-15% in adults.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common mode of presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Incidental finding","Biliary colic","Acute cholecystitis","Chronic cholecystitis","Choledocholithiasis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe majority of gallstones are asymptomatic and are often discovered \u003Cstrong\u003Eincidentally\u003C/strong\u003E during imaging for other conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnly about 20% of individuals with known, asymptomatic stones will ever develop clinically significant problems. When gallstones do become symptomatic, \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiliary colic\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common manifestation. Biliary colic describes a short episode of abdominal pain resulting from a gallstone causing transient obstruction of the cystic duct. \u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is inflammation of the gallbladder, usually due to obstruction of the cystic duct. \u003Cstrong\u003EChronic cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E develops after repeated episodes of inflammation. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholedocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to stones in the common bile duct, which occurs in a minority of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of asymptomatic gallstones alone is not an indication for cholecystectomy in most patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most gallstones (80%) are asymptomatic and found incidentally.","Symptomatic gallstones most commonly present with biliary colic.","Regular screening for asymptomatic gallstones is not recommended in the general population."],"references":["Dave HD, Shumway KR, Al Obaidi NM. Physiology, Biliary. [Updated 2022 Dec 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537107/","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., 